# OracleDB + Node.js Project

This project demonstrates how to connect a Node.js application to an Oracle 21c XE database using the `oracledb` library. It includes a simple use case of inserting and retrieving user data.

---

## üìÅ Project Structure

```

project/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ index.js
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ README.md

````

---

## üßë‚Äçüíª Prerequisites

- [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/) (v18+ recommended)
- [Oracle Database XE 21c](https://www.oracle.com/database/technologies/xe-downloads.html)
- Oracle client libraries (thin mode supported, no need for Instant Client in recent oracledb versions)

---

## üì¶ Installation

1. Clone this repository:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/oracle-node-project.git
cd oracle-node-project
````

2. Install dependencies:

```bash
npm install
```

3. Ensure the Oracle database service is running:

```bash
Get-Service OracleServiceXE   # (on PowerShell)
```

---

## üóÑÔ∏è Create Table & Insert Data in SQL\*Plus

Start SQL\*Plus:

```bash
sqlplus SYSTEM/your-password@XE
```

Create a table and insert data:

```sql
CREATE TABLE users (
  id NUMBER GENERATED BY DEFAULT AS IDENTITY,
  name VARCHAR2(100),
  phone_number VARCHAR2(15),
  PRIMARY KEY (id)
);

INSERT INTO users (name, phone_number)
VALUES ('Abhijeet', '+919075180122');

COMMIT;
```

---

## üìú `index.js`

```js
const oracledb = require('oracledb');

async function sendOTPToUser() {
  try {
    const connection = await oracledb.getConnection({
      user: 'SYSTEM',
      password: 'your-password',
      connectString: 'localhost/XE'
    });

    const result = await connection.execute(`SELECT name, phone_number FROM users`);
    for (const row of result.rows) {
      console.log(`Name: ${row[0]}\nPhone: ${row[1]}`);
    }

    await connection.close();
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('DB Error:', err);
  }
}

sendOTPToUser();
```

---

## ‚ñ∂Ô∏è Run the Project

```bash
node index.js
```

---

## üß† Notes

* If you see `ORA-00942: table or view does not exist`, verify that:

  * You're connected as the correct user (SYSTEM or the user that owns the table)
  * The `users` table exists (check with `SELECT * FROM user_tables;`)

